          "body": "The Asa section (vv. 9-24) is the chapter's positive centerpiece and the most detailed portrait of covenant reform in either kingdom to this point in Kings. The narrator stacks the reform actions in deliberate order: removal of male cult prostitutes from the land (v. 12 — the most visible symbol of Canaanite fertility religion); removal of the idols his fathers had made (v. 12 — dismantling dynastic idolatry); and the removal of Maacah his own mother from her position as queen mother (v. 13 — the most personally costly act). The gevirah, the queen mother, held formal political power in the Judahite court. Deposing her was not a domestic family dispute; it was a constitutional act. And the reason is specified: she had made a miphletset — a horrid, abominable image — as an Asherah. Asa cut it down and burned it at the Kidron. The combination of personal cost and public action is what the narrator means by a heart that is shalem. Reform that costs nothing proves nothing."
