          "body": "Read as a unit, 1 Kings 15 is a theological argument in narrative form. Two kingdoms, synchronized by regnal dates, are moving in opposite directions. Judah's movement is uneven — Abijam fails, Asa reforms significantly but incompletely, and the chapter closes with a hint of late-reign compromise — but the direction is sustained by the Davidic covenant and a wholly devoted heart. Israel's movement is circular: Jeroboam's sin begets Nadab's sin begets Baasha's sin. The north has no lamp, no covenant structure that outlasts individual kings, no reforming counterweight. The chapter's canonical function is to establish the divergent trajectories that will run through the rest of Kings: Judah sustained by grace through David's covenant, Israel accelerating toward judgment through Jeroboam's calf-worship. Both trajectories ultimately converge on the same horizon — exile — but by very different routes and for different reasons. The student who reads this chapter carefully will understand why the Exile came, and why the New Testament's announcement of the Son of David who finally fulfills what every lamp-holder failed to achieve is the only resolution the story can have."
